msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:46
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 2 - Key concepts of data quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide3.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 3 - Data quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:63
msgid ""
"Before we begin, I’d like to take a moment to explain why data quality is "
"important. Cleanliness is next to Godliness is an expression that we "
"sometimes use to describe the importance of data quality. In this case, "
"Godliness can be understood as holiness, and when something is holy it is "
"considered by many to be worthy of our trust.    So, in the case of data "
"quality, we are more likely to trust and to use data that has been cleaned "
"and cared for."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:70
msgid ""
"Photo: GBIF: https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/2611012759 Rhododendron "
"kasangiae D.G. Long & Rushforth Rights holder: Sangay Wangchuk "
"License: http://creativeco...censes/by-nc/4.0/ Reference: https://www."
"inatu...g/photos/68350578"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide4.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 4 - Data quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:80
msgid ""
"Stepping back into the domain of biodiversity informatics, the classic "
"definition of data quality was coined in 2005 by Arthur Chapman. He wrote:   "
"“data quality is related to use and cannot be assessed independently of the "
"user. In a database, the data have no actual quality or value (Dalcin 2004); "
"they only have potential value that is realized when someone uses the data "
"to do something useful. Information quality relates to its ability to "
"satisfy its customers and to meet customers’ needs (English 1999).” Arthur "
"Chapman”   And so, for us, as individuals who are responsible for "
"maintaining data, we want the data we publish to be as satisfying to all of "
"our potential users as possible. To do this, we seek to provide the highest "
"quality data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:87
msgid ""
"Photo: GBIF: https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/2634451942 Dendrochirus zebra "
"(Cuvier, 1829)  Rights holder: Ryan Yue Wah Chan License: http://"
"creativeco...censes/by-nc/4.0/ Reference: https://www.inatu...g/"
"photos/76358738"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - Data quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:95
msgid ""
"To help you to accomplish this task, we will explore Fitness for Use. We "
"will also explore the Measures of Quality, specifically, Correctness and "
"Consistency.    These are important concepts that you will need to know and "
"be able to articulate about your own data or data that you maintain."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:102
msgid ""
"Photo: GBIF: https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/2238803261 Papilio paris "
"Linnaeus, 1758 Rights holder: CheongWeei Gan License: http://creativeco..."
"censes/by-nc/4.0/ Reference: https://www.inatu...g/photos/35832506"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:103
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:106
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Fitness for use in the real world*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:108
msgid ""
"Let’s begin with an example of Fitness for Use. A shoemaker creates a pair "
"of clogs for the purpose of covering a person’s feet, just like those at the "
"top of this image."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:110
msgid ""
"Image Reference: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Schuhmacher-1568.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:111
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:114
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Fitness for use in the real world*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:118
msgid ""
"When the shoemaker made these shoes, did he know that this girl would use "
"them for dancing?   Maybe."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:120
msgid ""
"Image Reference: https://www.publicdomainpictures.net/en/view-image.php?"
"image=157723&picture=&jazyk=CN"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:121
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:124
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Fitness for use in the real world*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:130
msgid ""
"Do you think that the same shoemaker knew that a gardener might one day use "
"the shoes as plant pots?   Maybe not.    Image Reference: Sharon Grant "
"[https://www.flickr.com/photos/rondls_pics/4941594970/in/"
"album-72157616943444786/]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Fitness for use*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:138
msgid ""
"We often hear people talk about data’s Fitness for Use in the ecological "
"sciences, but what we need to remember is that data is not inherently good "
"or bad. Rather it is the user of the data who gives data its value.    For "
"example, for one person, data identified to the level of Genus may be "
"sufficient to run predictive models of ecological niches. For a person "
"studying a particular taxon, that same genus-level data will be much less "
"useful than more detailed occurrences with subspecies information."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:145
msgid ""
"Photo: GBIF: https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/1621797237 Calotes mystaceus "
"Duméril & Bibron, 1837 Rights holder: robbythai License: http://creativeco..."
"censes/by-nc/4.0/ Reference: https://www.inatu...rg/photos/9949104"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:149
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Fitness for use*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:156
msgid ""
"So, what is Fitness for Use and how does it relate to data?   When Chapman "
"discusses Fitness for Use, he says that once a dataset has been created and "
"shared there are two primary perspectives on how those data might be used; "
"the perspective of the creator and the perspective of the user.    To help "
"somebody to decide if your data is trustworthy or useful enough for them to "
"use, you have to understand your data and how to convey those data to the "
"potential user. These are some of the important questions about the "
"metadata, or characteristics of your data, that you should be able to answer "
"and share with others:  "
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:157
msgid ""
"How Accessible are your data? How easily can someone access your data? "
"People can’t use the data if they can’t find the data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:158
msgid ""
"How Accurate are your data? Can your data be trusted? For example, are your "
"identifications current and were they made by known experts?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:159
msgid ""
"How Timely are they? When will the data be made available? How often are "
"they updated?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:160
msgid ""
"How Complete or Comprehensive are the data? Which parts of your dataset are "
"documented fully? How well do the data cover a particular time, place, or "
"domain?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:161
msgid ""
"How Consistent are they? Is the data in each field always of the same type? "
"Was the data collected using the same documented protocols?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:162
msgid ""
"How Relevant are they? How similar is this dataset to others that have been "
"used successfully for the same purpose?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:163
msgid ""
"How Detailed are the data? How much resolution is there in your data? At "
"what scale can they be used for mapping?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:164
msgid ""
"Is the data Easy to interpret? Is the dataset documented in a clear and "
"concise way? If your documents are handwritten, are they legible?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:171
msgid ""
"Photo: GBIF: https://www.gbif.org/occurrence/1932569869 Amphidromus "
"goldbergi Thach & F. Huber, 2018 Rights holder: Manual Caballer "
"License: http://creativeco.../licenses/by/4.0/ Identifier: https://"
"mediaphoto.mnhn.fr/media/1546617441086USKcRv3tfQkB8mZo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:172
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:175
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Measures of quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:177
msgid ""
"While Fitness for Use is subjective, measures of data quality are much less "
"so. Chapman states that:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:179
msgid ""
"\"All data include error – there is no escaping it! It is knowing what the "
"error is that is important, and knowing if the error is within acceptable "
"limits for the purpose to which the data are to be put. (Chapman 2005)”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:180
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide12.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:183
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 12 - Measures of quality*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:187
msgid ""
"We can use two measures of quality, Correctness and Consistency, to help us "
"to document these inherent errors in data.    Correctness, sometimes called "
"accuracy, is “How close the recorded value is to the actual, real-world "
"value”. "
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:191
msgid ""
"In this diagram accuracy is how close a given dot is to the centre of the "
"target.    Consistency, sometimes called precision, is “How often you get it "
"right”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:195
msgid ""
"In this diagram, precision is how close the dots are together irrespective "
"of how close they are to the centre of the target.    These are measures of "
"how well the data gatherer was able to capture the true value being "
"investigated. Knowing these properties of your data will help you to "
"understand the ways in which you can and cannot clean, validate and process "
"the data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:196
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide13.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 13 - Measures of quality - Accuracy vs precision*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:201
msgid ""
"This image provides a clear set of illustrations of accuracy and precision. "
"This may be a good image to keep with you when you have to explain these "
"concepts to others."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:203
msgid ""
"Image source: https://kaiserscience.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/"
"precision_accuracy.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:204
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide14.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:207
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 14 - Measures of quality correctness*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:211
msgid ""
"Let’s look at some examples of Correctness, or accuracy, and how it can help "
"us think about the practicalities of data cleaning. Remember that "
"Correctness is how close you are to the center of a target.    Let’s look at "
"an example."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:212
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide15.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:215
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 15 - Measures of quality correctness - Example 1*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:221
msgid ""
"For this example let’s imagine your dataset contains records of fossil bird "
"specimens from the Early Triassic Period. The taxonomic name for a number of "
"specimens in your dataset is recorded as Thismia.    Do you know if Thismia "
"is a taxon of ancient birds?   Image reference: https://commons.wikimedia."
"org/wiki/File:Archaeopteryx_fossil.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:222
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide16.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:225
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 16 - Measures of quality correctness - Example 1*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:238
msgid ""
"In this case, the answer is no!    Thismia is a very rare plant from the "
"State of Illinois in the United States.    As a result, the correctness, or "
"accuracy, of the taxonomic name is low. Perhaps because the data entry "
"technician was not a paleontologist. As a result, all of the names in the "
"dataset might need to be checked and corrected by an expert before the data "
"could be used.    Photo: GBIF: (n/a)  Thismia rodwayi Rights holder: Tindo2 "
"License: http://creativeco...censes/by-nc/4.0/ Reference(n/a): https://www."
"inaturalist.org/photos/596775?size=large"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:239
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide17.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:242
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 17 - Measures of quality correctness - Example 2*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:246
msgid ""
"Let’s look at another example. Here, your dataset contains specimens "
"collected in a place called Kalamazoo by a scientist named Richard Spruce.  "
"  We must ask ourselves:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:248
msgid "Is 49007 the right postal code for Kalamazoo?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:250
msgid "Did Richard Spruce collect in Michigan?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide18.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:254
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 18 - Measures of quality correctness - Example 2*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:256
msgid ""
"In this case, the answer is yes to our first question, 49007 is a postal "
"code for Kalamazoo, so the accuracy of the locality is good, but what about "
"the collector, Richard Spruce?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:260
msgid ""
"Image references: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Spruce#/media/File:"
"Spruce_Richard.jpg https://archive.org/details/notesofbotanisto21908spru"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide19.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:264
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 19 - Measures of quality correctness - Example 2*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:270
msgid ""
"There is, in fact, a famous botanist named Richard Spruce. He was born in "
"1817 and died in 1893, but he conducted his collecting in the Amazon Basin "
"and Andes mountains in South America. Something is not quite right, so we "
"need to find out more about the collector before we can be confident in the "
"correctness of these data.    Image references: https://en.wikipedia.org/"
"wiki/Richard_Spruce#/media/File:Spruce_Richard.jpg https://archive.org/"
"details/notesofbotanisto21908spru"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:271
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide20.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:274
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 20 - Measures of quality consistency*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:280
msgid ""
"Let’s take a look now at what Consistency, or precision, means to data.    "
"Consistency represents how many times you get the same answer, regardless of "
"where the center of the target lies.    For example, your dataset contains "
"botanical occurrences including a field, or column, named “Full Name”. This "
"field contains the name of the specimen collector. As you can see there are "
"five different names, but how many unique collectors are there? Can you tell "
"just by looking at the names?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:281
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide21.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:284
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 21 - Measures of quality consistency*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:296
msgid ""
"Sometimes, if you are familiar with the dataset, you might know how many "
"collectors are represented just by looking at the data, but if you don’t "
"know these data well, you might need to do some research, ask some questions "
"or look at the original field notes.    In this example, if you guessed that "
"these five names represent two or three unique collectors, you would be "
"right:   In blue, Joseph Dalton Hooker AND Hook.f. are the same person. Hook."
"f. is the abbreviation used for Joseph Dalton Hooker (1817-1911).    In "
"green, W. J. Hooker and Hook. are the same person.  Hook. is the "
"abbreviation for William Jackson Hooker (1785-1865). William was actually "
"Joseph’s father.    Finally, in the red, there is “Hooker, J.” This entry "
"could be an error or typo of either Joseph or William Hooker, OR it could be "
"a third person with a similar name. Thus, more research would be needed to "
"clarify these data.    Reference: http://www.ipni.org/ipni/advAuthorSearch."
"do;jsessionid=087C235AF7757EF21CA33FF5325C94C7?"
"find_forename=&find_surname=Hooker&find_abbreviation=&find_isoCountry=&output_format=normal&back_page=authorsearch&query_type=by_query"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:297
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide22.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 22 - Data cleaning*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:312
msgid ""
"We have just discussed several simple illustrations of two measures of data "
"quality. These examples should give you a basic understanding about how to "
"identify the inaccuracies and imprecisions in data.    How we document and "
"fix these issues or errors is a process that we call data cleaning.  More "
"specifically:   Data cleaning is the process of correcting or removing dirty "
"data caused by contradictions, disparities, keying mistakes, missing bits, "
"and more. It also includes validation of the changes made, and may require "
"normalization.    Our data cleaning, or lack thereof, will affect how data "
"users perceive your data’s fitness for use.    It is not necessary for you "
"to do all the data cleaning yourself, in fact, a common misconception is "
"that all errors MUST be fixed before you can share your data.    The truth "
"is that you can only clean as much data as your time, knowledge, and "
"resources permit. As a result, it is essential to document what you know and "
"what you do not know about your data so that when you do share them, data "
"users will know the level of the quality of your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-data-quality.adoc:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-data-quality-Slide23.png"
msgstr ""

